{
  "text": "Clostridial neurotoxins are useful in understanding membrane trafficking events concerning the SNARE mechanism because they inhibit neural transmission through each metalloprotease activity specific to each SNARE component [CITATION_1] . Among them, neurotoxin C1 of Clostridium botulinum cleaves syntaxin [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , and as a result, syntaxin is released from the plasmalemma, and the neurotransmitter release is blocked [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Therefore, neurotoxin C1 can deplete membrane-bound syntaxin in situ.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "45069991",
    "[CITATION_2]": "30078419",
    "[CITATION_3]": "46619385",
